- Work with the RC Centre for Professional Skills team and BComm course instructors and their TAs on deliverables related to the development of professional skills. Duties may include facilitating group and individual appointments with students and providing support for students in developing both oral and written communication skills, with an emphasis on oral communication skills and presentation skills. This could include:
- providing oral communication and presentation coaching and feedback;
- providing feedback on drafts of video-based oral communication assessments and support for effective video presentations;
- providing support for both individual and group presentations.
- providing feedback on drafts of written assignments and support for building effective writing skills;
- providing support for both individual and group written assignments.
- Providing feedback on structure, design, and presentation of slide decks.

Duties and appointments will be delivered both online (using WCOnline and Zoom ) and in-person (to be scheduled in consultation with the Communications/Presentations TA.

Duties may also include the development of teaching resources related to oral or written communication skills, or presentation skills.

Work with the RC Centre for Professional Skills team and Commerce course instructors and their TAs on deliverables related to the development of professional skills (e.g. professional written and oral communication, teamwork skills, intercultural competencies). Duties may include:
- providing support for the grading of online modules embedded in RC courses;
- providing support for grading assignments focused on professional skills;
- helping to create/design resources for students related to their skill development;
- providing overall support for CPS instructional programming.

Duties may also include facilitating or co-facilitating TA training or marking calibration sessions and/or providing research support on pedagogical projects.

qualifications_minimum:
In addition to the on-line application, you must submit a writing sample (individually authored and no more than four pages) to Josie Alaimo or email to: josie.alaimo@utoronto.ca
 Current PhD student; 
At least two years' experience as a course TA, whether leading tutorials/ labs, in-class instruction, or grading;
Excellent oral communication and interpersonal skills, particularly the ability to work effectively with and show tact when communicating with administrators, course instructors and TAs;
Strong administrative skills, including ability to schedule meetings and training sessions, plan and document work;
 Strong time management skills with ability to meet multiple deadlines;
Strong facilitation and presentation skills and/or experience leading/facilitating workshops;
Evidence of superior writing skills in their discipline (writing sample must be individually authored)
